## Controversies

*Fallout 76* Power Armor [edition](special)(special edition) drew controversy upon release. Bethesda advertised that the edition would include a [canvas](canvas) [bag](duffel)(duffel bag), but a [nylon](nylon) one was included instead. Responding to customer complaints, Bethesda claimed that the bag had to be changed due to unavailability of materials, and initially stated the intention to take no action. The publisher received criticism for not making the change known beforehand, with *[Eurogamer](Eurogamer)* pointing out that the bag's description on Bethesda's website had only changed to read "nylon" after complaints had been submitted. Bethesda later offered affected customers free in-game currency of 500 atoms as compensation, equivalent to . Critics pointed out this amount of currency was not enough to purchase the in-game postman uniform (700 atoms), which includes a canvas bag. Additionally, it was discovered that Bethesda had produced a different *Fallout 76*–themed canvas bag and given them for free to [influencers](online)(Internet celebrity), further adding to the fan outrage. Bethesda announced on December 3, 2018, that they would be producing canvas bags for all owners of the Power Armor special edition, which were ultimately said to be shipping "in four to six months." In June 2019, the bags were delivered to customers.

A [breach](data)(data breach) occurred on December 5, 2018, when a [glitch](glitch) in Bethesda's [system](support)(Issue tracking system) revealed personal information of approximately 65 *Fallout 76* customers who had submitted a support ticket to receive the canvas bag. Users were able to open and close tickets of other customers and view personal information, including names, addresses, emails and partial credit card information. In a statement given to *[Technica](Ars)(Ars Technica)*, Bethesda said that the breach occurred via "an error with our customer support website" and that they are "investigating the incident and will provide additional updates as we learn more". The publisher clarified that the only information leaked were details that the support site would have requested, rather than credit card numbers or passwords, and that they would notify all affected customers.

In 2018, Bethesda partnered with the Silver Screen Bottling Company to create "Nuka Dark Rum", an alcoholic beverage based on the in-game "Nuka-Cola Dark" introduced in the *[4: Nuka-World](Fallout)(Fallout 4: Nuka-World)* [add-on](Downloadable content). The rum was available to be pre-ordered in August 2018 for . While its release was expected to coincide with the launch of *Fallout 76*, the rum was delayed and was shipped instead in late December 2018. Upon receiving it, fans criticized the fact that the rum bottle advertised, previously expected to be a bottle in the missile-like shape of the in-game Nuka-Cola item, had turned out to be a standard glass bottle encased in a large plastic cover. The rum's asking price of $80 was subsequently condemned from expectations that the design would be of high quality, since none of the marketing had stated what the bottles would be made of.

In September 2019, collectible "Nuka Cola"–themed *Fallout* helmets produced by Chronicle Collectibles, of which only 32 of the 20,000 manufactured were sold, were recalled by the [Consumer Product Safety Commission](U.S.)(U.S. Consumer Product Safety Commission) due to containing high levels of mold and posing a health risk. No incidents or injuries were reported. [GameStop](GameStop), which sold the helmets, notified all customers who had purchased a helmet and offered them a full refund.

In June 2022, a *Kotaku* article published reports from ten anonymous former employees of Bethesda and its parent company [Media](ZeniMax)(ZeniMax Media) of severe mismanagement during *Fallout 76*s development. The reports claimed that [crunch](Crunch (video games)) had been enforced, leading to an "exodus" of senior developers from the company. The loss of staff led to Bethesda borrowing developers working on [Studios](Arkane)(Arkane Studios)' *[Redfall](Redfall)* and Bethesda's *[Starfield](Starfield (video game))* to assist with *Fallout 76*. Other alleged issues included technical problems with the game's design and engine, as well as these concerns being ignored by senior management. The sources expressed cynicism towards an improvement of working conditions at Bethesda (following their acquisition by Microsoft), saying "It would be great if something like [ABetterABK](ABK Workers Alliance) existed for Bethesda [...] But everyone is terrified...because [Bethesda] HR is super cutthroat."

The controversy surrounding the Fallout 76 Power Armor edition's physical item centered on the replacement of a promised canvas duffel bag with a nylon one. Initially advertised as a canvas bag, the change was made due to material unavailability, but Bethesda did not inform customers beforehand. This led to backlash, especially since the company later offered only 500 in-game atoms (equivalent to $5) as compensation — an amount insufficient to buy the in-game postman uniform, which includes a canvas bag. Further outrage erupted when it was revealed that Bethesda had produced canvas bags for influencers but not for paying customers. Eventually, Bethesda committed to shipping free canvas bags to all affected customers, which were delivered in June 2019.

[[in 2018–2019](File:Boygenius.png|thumb|right|Boygenius)]

Bridgers has called the formation of the group "kind of an accident," wherein each of the members were simply fans of each other's work and then became friends. The three became close and shared their frustrations of constantly being compared to each other as "[in rock](women)(women in rock)" despite their considerably different musical styles. Dacus has commented that the idea of women in music "should not be remarkable whatsoever," with Bridgers adding, "it's not a genre." Each has spoken on the tendency of the music industry to pit women against each other, and the group was formed in part to reject this idea. "I hope people see the three of us and know there isn't competition," Dacus has said. "You don't have to compete with your contemporaries. You can make something good with people you admire."

Baker had joked to Dacus years before about a "pipe dream" that they could one day all form a band. The three decided to book a [tour](co-headlining)(Julien Baker and Phoebe Bridgers with Lucy Dacus Tour) in early 2018, and they originally planned to record a single or a [version](cover)(cover version) so that they could perform something together on stage. Upon meeting up that summer, however, they found themselves overwhelmed with ideas, and they ended up forming the band, writing, recording, and self-producing the *[Boygenius](Boygenius (EP))* [EP](Extended play) in four days, with the process involving almost exclusively women.

Each brought one full song and one incomplete idea with them to the group. They sought to create an environment free of the competitiveness and "bravado" they had often encountered in previous experiences, and they have remarked that the absence of adult men in the process proved significant, allowing them to relate to each other openly without constantly having to explain themselves. The record was met with universal acclaim from critics and audiences alike; it was named the 12th best album of 2018 by [Music](NPR)(NPR Music), despite being only an [EP](Extended play). Their subsequent [tour](Julien Baker and Phoebe Bridgers with Lucy Dacus Tour) that November saw them performing all across the U.S., as well as on *[Night with Seth Meyers](Late)(Late Night with Seth Meyers)* and the [Desk](Tiny)(List of Tiny Desk Concerts).
The three musicians who formed the indie rock supergroup boygenius in 2018 are Julien Baker, Phoebe Bridgers, and Lucy Dacus.

The **unicursal hexagram** is a [hexagram](hexagram) or six-pointed star that can be traced or drawn [unicursally](unicursal curve), in one continuous line rather than by two overlaid triangles. The hexagram can also be depicted inside a circle with the points touching it. It is often depicted in an interlaced form with the lines of the hexagram passing over and under one another to form a [knot](knot (mathematics)). Because the development of rock and roll was an evolutionary process, no single record can be identified as unambiguously "the first" rock and roll record.[Dawson](Jim)(Jim Dawson) and Steve Propes, ''[Was The First Rock'n'Roll Record](What)(iarchive:whatwasfirstrock0000daws)'', 1992,  Contenders for the title of "[rock and roll record](first)(first rock and roll record)" include [Rosetta Tharpe](Sister)(Sister Rosetta Tharpe)'s "[Things Happening Every Day](Strange)(Strange Things Happening Every Day)" (1944), "[All Right](That's)(That's All Right)" by [Crudup](Arthur)(Arthur Crudup) (1946),  "[It On Over](Move)(Move It On Over (song))" by [Williams](Hank)(Hank Williams) (1947), "[Fat Man](The)(The Fat Man (song))" by [Domino](Fats)(Fats Domino) (1949), [Carter](Goree)(Goree Carter)'s "[Awhile](Rock)(Rock Awhile)" (1949),[Palmer](Robert)(Robert Palmer (writer)), "Church of the Sonic Guitar", pp. 13–38 in Anthony DeCurtis, *Present Tense*, [University Press](Duke)(Duke University Press), 1992, p. 19.  and [Preston](Jimmy)(Jimmy Preston)'s "[the Joint](Rock)(Rock the Joint)" (1949) (later [covered](cover version) by [Haley & His Comets](Bill)(Bill Haley & His Comets) in 1952),

This is often cited as the first rock n' roll record.M. Campbell, ed., *Popular Music in America: and the Beat Goes on* (Boston, Massachusetts: Cengage Learning, 3rd ed., 2008), , pp. 157–8. In an interview however, Ike Turner offered this comment: "I don't think that 'Rocket 88' is rock 'n' roll. [[File:BillHaley.JPG|upright=1.05|thumb|[Haley](Bill)(Bill Haley) and his Comets performing in the 1954 Universal International film *Round Up of Rhythm*]]

In terms of its wide cultural impact across society in the US and elsewhere, [Haley](Bill)(Bill Haley (musician))'s "[Around the Clock](Rock)(Rock Around the Clock)", recorded in April 1954 but not a commercial success until the following year, is generally recognized as an important milestone, but it was preceded by many recordings from earlier decades in which elements of rock and roll can be clearly discerned.Robert Palmer, "Rock Begins", in *[Stone](Rolling)(Rolling Stone) Illustrated History of Rock and Roll*, 1976/1980,  (UK edition), pp. 3–14.

Journalist [Petridis](Alexis)(Alexis Petridis) argued that neither Haley's "Rock Around the Clock" nor Presley's version of "That's Alright Mama" heralded a new genre: "They were simply the first white artists' interpretations of a sound already well-established by black musicians almost a decade before. It was a raucous, driving, unnamed variant of rhythm and blues that came complete with lyrics that talked about rocking".

Other artists with early rock and roll hits included [Berry](Chuck)(Chuck Berry), [Diddley](Bo)(Bo Diddley), [Richard](Little)(Little Richard), [Lee Lewis](Jerry)(Jerry Lee Lewis), and [Vincent](Gene)(Gene Vincent). Chuck Berry's 1955 classic "[Maybellene](Maybellene)" in particular features a [distorted](distortion (music)) [guitar](electric)(electric guitar) solo with warm [overtone](overtone)s created by his small [amplifier](valve)(valve amplifier). Also in 1955, Bo Diddley introduced the "[Diddley beat](Bo)(Bo Diddley beat)" and a unique electric guitar style,P. Buckley, *The rough guide to rock* (Rough Guides, 3rd ed., 2003), p. 21. influenced by [African](Music of Africa) and [music](Afro-Cuban)(Afro-Cuban music) and in turn influencing many later artists.

Chuck Berry is often referred to as the "Architect of Rock and Roll." He is credited with putting together the essential elements of rock and roll music, particularly through his innovative use of the electric guitar, his storytelling lyrics, and his energetic stage performances. As noted, in 2017, music critic Robert Christgau declared that "Chuck Berry did in fact invent rock 'n' roll," stating that Berry came the closest of any single figure to being the one who put all the essential pieces together. His 1955 classic song "Maybellene" is considered a landmark in the genre, showcasing a distorted electric guitar solo and a driving rhythm that became central to rock and roll.

## Career

[[Galecki 2008.JPG|thumb|left|upright|Galecki in July 2008](File:Johnny)]

After working in the Chicago theatre scene as a young child, Galecki made his onscreen acting debut in the 1987 CBS miniseries *[Ordained](Murder)(Murder Ordained)* with [Williams](JoBeth)(JoBeth Williams) and future *Roseanne* co-star [Goodman](John)(John Goodman). In 1989, Galecki portrayed Rusty Griswold in ''[Lampoon's Christmas Vacation](National)(National Lampoon's Christmas Vacation)''. In 1990, he was cast as Danny Nash, the son of [Urich](Robert)(Robert Urich)'s lead character, on the [NBC](NBC) comedy *[Dreamer](American)(American Dreamer (TV series))*; the following season, he was a regular cast member on the ABC sitcom *[Billy](Billy (1992 TV series))*, a spin-off from *[of the Class](Head)(Head of the Class)*. He appeared in one episode of [*Blossom*](Blossom (TV series)) in 1991, opposite his future *[Big Bang Theory](The)(The Big Bang Theory)* co-star [Bialik](Mayim)(Mayim Bialik). He played a young delinquent in *[Family Torn Apart](A)(A Family Torn Apart)*, a 1993 TV movie based on a true story about a [killer](serial)(serial killer).

During his run on *Billy*, Galecki began making guest appearances on the hit ABC sitcom *[Roseanne](Roseanne)* as the younger brother of Mark Healy ([Quinn](Glenn)(Glenn Quinn)), who began a relationship with Darlene Conner ([Gilbert](Sara)(Sara Gilbert)). Introduced in his first appearance as Kevin Healy, his name was soon changed to [David](List of Roseanne characters#David Healy). After a few more guest shots, Galecki was named a permanent *Roseanne* cast member from the fall of 1992 onward, after the cancellation of *Billy*. He would remain in the role of David Healy until the end of *Roseanne*'s run in 1997, with the character eventually marrying Darlene and fathering two children with her. Galecki's character on *The Big Bang Theory* would also have a short-lived relationship with Gilbert's character on the same show.

Galecki also appeared in the 1995 music video for the [Matthews Band](Dave)(Dave Matthews Band) song "[Satellite](Satellite (Dave Matthews Band song))".

After *Roseanne* ended, Galecki had small roles in a string of films, including the 1997 summer [film](slasher)(slasher film) *[Know What You Did Last Summer](I)(I Know What You Did Last Summer)* (as the killer's first victim),  *[Bean](Bean (film))* (1997), *[Opposite of Sex](The)(The Opposite of Sex)* (1998), *[Bounce](Bounce (film))* (2000) and *[Sky](Vanilla)(Vanilla Sky)* (2001). He had larger roles in the 1997 film *[Kings](Suicide)(Suicide Kings)* and the 2003 film *[Bookies](Bookies (film))*, a comedy thriller film about four college students. Galecki appeared as a golfer in a 2005 episode of *[Name Is Earl](My)(My Name Is Earl)* entitled "Stole Beer from a Golfer".

In 2005, Galecki played Mark Corrigan in a pilot for a US adaptation of the British sitcom [Show*](*Peep)(Peep Show (British TV series)). He played a character named Trouty on [TBS](TBS (TV network))'s sitcom *[Boys](My)(My Boys)*, and the half-brother of the main characters, sisters Hope Shanowski and Faith Fairfield, in the sitcom *[& Faith](Hope)(Hope & Faith)*. Galecki originated the role of Alex, a male prostitute, in the play *[Little Dog Laughed](The)(The Little Dog Laughed (play))* by [Carter Beane](Douglas)(Douglas Carter Beane), in 2006 at [Stage Theater](Second)(Second Stage Theater). He stayed in the role for the play's [Broadway](Broadway theater) run at the [Theatre](Cort)(Cort Theatre) in late 2006 and early 2007. Galecki said at the time, "At its core, the play is about what we all sacrifice to be successful, whatever our careers or goals." The play was a commercial and critical success, and Galecki won a [Theater World Award](2007)(Theater World Award#2007) for his performance.

[[File:Johnny Galecki at PaleyFest 2013.jpg|thumb|upright|Galecki at [PaleyFest](PaleyFest) 2013]]

Galecki played [Hofstadter](Leonard)(Leonard Hofstadter) in the [CBS](CBS) sitcom *[Big Bang Theory](The)(The Big Bang Theory)*, which ran from 2007 to 2019 and was, for most of its run, among the top three most popular television comedies in the US. Galecki was originally asked to play the role of [Cooper](Sheldon)(Sheldon Cooper), but he felt he was better suited for the role of Leonard, and Sheldon's role was eventually given to [Parsons](Jim)(Jim Parsons). During the show's run, two of Galecki's former *Roseanne* co-stars appeared on the show: [Gilbert](Sara)(Sara Gilbert) (as [Winkle](Leslie)(Leslie Winkle), Leonard's colleague) and [Metcalf](Laurie)(Laurie Metcalf) (as Mary Cooper, Sheldon's mother). Galecki is a [cellist](cello), a talent that was used on the show. Until 2013, Galecki and his *Big Bang* co-stars [Cuoco](Kaley)(Kaley Cuoco) and Jim Parsons each earned US$325,000 per episode.Battaglio, Stephen; Schneider, Michael (August 26, 2013). "What They Earn". *[Guide](TV)(TV Guide)*. pp. 16 – 20. By 2014, the three were earning US$1 million per episode.

Galecki appeared briefly in the 2008 superhero comedy *[Hancock](Hancock (film))*, alongside [Smith](Will)(Will Smith) and [Bateman](Jason)(Jason Bateman). In July 2011, he played a parody version of himself in three episodes of *[Entourage](Entourage (U.S. TV series))*. He also appeared in the film *[Time](In)(In Time)* (2011) with [Timberlake](Justin)(Justin Timberlake) and [Seyfried](Amanda)(Amanda Seyfried).

Galecki appeared in one episode of the [revival of *Roseanne*](2018)(Roseanne (season 10)) on ABC. The show, despite its high ratings, was cancelled after [Barr](Roseanne)(Roseanne Barr) posted a racist and controversial tweet about [Jarrett](Valerie)(Valerie Jarrett). *Roseanne* was replaced by a new program, *[Conners](The)(The Conners)*, which premiered in October 2018 and featured the same cast without Barr. Galecki has occasionally appeared as David on *The Conners*.

Johnny Galecki plays the cello, an instrument he has played since childhood. This talent was incorporated into his character, Leonard Hofstadter, on *The Big Bang Theory*, where Leonard is also portrayed as a skilled cellist.

#### Troy VIIa

Troy VIIa was the final layer of the Late Bronze Age city. It was built soon after the destruction of Troy VI, seemingly by its previous inhabitants. The builders reused many of the earlier city's surviving structures, notably its citadel wall, which they renovated with additional stone towers and mudbrick breastworks. Numerous small houses were added inside the citadel, filling in formerly open areas. New houses were also built in the lower city, whose area appears to have been greater in Troy VIIa than in Troy VI. In many of these houses, archaeologists found enormous storage jars called [pithoi](pithos) buried in the ground. Troy VIIa seems to have been built by survivors of Troy VI's destruction, as evidenced by continuity in material culture. However, the character of the city appears to have changed, the citadel growing crowded and foreign imports declining.

The city was destroyed around 1180 BC, roughly contemporary with the [Bronze Age collapse](Late)(Late Bronze Age collapse) but subsequent to the [of the Mycenaean palaces](destruction)(Mycenaean Greece#Collapse or postpalatial Bronze Age (c. 1200–1050 BC)). ## Black Cross emblem

[[File:War Ensign of Prussia (1816).svg|thumb|[flag of Prussia](War)(Flag of Prussia) (1816)]]

The Black Cross (*Schwarzes Kreuz*) is the emblem used by the [Army](Prussian)(Prussian Army) and Germany's army from 1871 to the present. It was designed on the occasion of the [Campaign of 1813](German)(German Campaign of 1813), when [Wilhelm III of Prussia](Friedrich)(Friedrich Wilhelm III of Prussia) commissioned the Iron Cross as the first military decoration open to all ranks, including enlisted men. From this time, the Black Cross was featured on the [war flag](Prussian)(Flag of Prussia) alongside the Black Eagle. It was designed by neoclassical architect [Friedrich Schinkel](Karl)(Karl Friedrich Schinkel), based on Friedrich Wilhelm III. The design is ultimately derivative of the [cross](black)(Black Cross (Teutonic Order)) used by the [Order](Teutonic)(Teutonic Order). This heraldic cross took various forms throughout the order's history, including a [cross](Latin)(Latin cross), a [potent](cross)(cross potent), [fleury](cross)(cross fleury), and occasionally also a [pattée](cross)(cross pattée).

When the [Quadriga](Quadriga) of the Goddess of Peace was retrieved from Paris at Napoleon's fall, it was re-established atop Berlin's [Gate](Brandenburg)(Brandenburg Gate). An Iron Cross was inserted into Peace's [laurel](bay laurel) [wreath](wreath), making her into a [of Victory](Goddess)(Victoria (mythology)). In 1821 Schinkel crowned the top of his design of the [Monument for the Liberation Wars](National)(Prussian National Monument for the Liberation Wars) with an Iron Cross, becoming name-giving as [Kreuzberg](Kreuzberg (Tempelhofer Berge)) (cross mountain) for the hill it stands on and, 100 years later, for the [quarter](homonymous)(Kreuzberg) adjacent to it.Klaus-Dieter Wille, *Spaziergänge in Kreuzberg*, Berlin: Haude & Spener, 1986, (=Berliner Kaleidoskop: Schriften zur Berliner Kunst- und Kulturgeschichte; vol. 32), p. 21. .

The Black Cross was used on the naval and combat flags of the [Empire](German)(German Empire). The Black Cross was used as the German Army symbol until 1915 when a simpler Balkenkreuz replaced it. The *[Reichswehr](Reichswehr)* of the [Republic](Weimar)(Weimar Republic) (1921–35), the *[Wehrmacht](Wehrmacht)* of [Germany](Nazi)(Nazi Germany) (1935–46), and the *[Bundeswehr](Bundeswehr)* (1 October 1956 to present) also inherited the use of the emblem in various forms. The traditional design in black is used on armored vehicles and aircraft, while after [reunification](German)(German reunification), a new creation in blue and silver was introduced for use in other contexts.

The Black Cross emblem used by the Prussian and German armies was designed by the neoclassical architect **Friedrich Schinkel**, based on the vision of Friedrich Wilhelm III of Prussia. The design was created during the Wars of Liberation in 1813 and is ultimately derived from the cross used by the Teutonic Order.

### Belyayev circle

[[File:Belyayev by Repin.jpg|thumb|upright|right|alt=A middle-aged man with medium-length dark hair and a beard, wearing a dark suit, with one hand in his trouser pocket and the other hand on his chin|Portrait by [Repin](Ilya)(Ilya Repin) of [P. Belyayev](M.)(Mitrofan Belyayev), founder of the Russian Symphony Concerts]]

Rimsky-Korsakov wrote that he became acquainted with budding music patron [Belyayev](Mitrofan)(Mitrofan Belyayev) (M. P. Belaieff) in Moscow in 1882.Rimsky-Korsakov, *My Musical Life*, p. 261. Belyayev was one of a growing coterie of Russian nouveau-riche industrialists who became patrons of the arts in mid- to late-19th century Russia; their number included railway magnate [Mamontov](Savva)(Savva Mamontov) and textile manufacturer [Tretyakov](Pavel)(Pavel Tretyakov).Figes, pp. 195–97; Maes, 173–74, 196–97. Belyayev, Mamontov and Tretyakov "wanted to contribute conspicuously to public life".Taruskin, p. 49. They had worked their way into wealth, and being Slavophiles in their national outlook believed in the greater glory of Russia. Owing to this belief, they were more likely than the aristocracy to support native talent, and were more inclined to support nationalist artists over cosmopolitan ones.Taruskin, *Stravinsky*, p. 42. This preference paralleled a general upsurge in nationalism and Russophilia that became prevalent in mainstream Russian art and society.Taruskin, *Stravinsky*, p. 44.

By 1883 Rimsky-Korsakov had become a regular visitor to the weekly "quartet Fridays" ("Les Vendredis") held at Belyayev's home in Saint Petersburg.Rimsky-Korsakov, *My Musical Life*, p. 269. Belyayev, who had already taken a keen interest in the musical future of the teenage [Glazunov](Alexander)(Alexander Glazunov), rented a hall and hired an orchestra in 1884 to play Glazunov's First Symphony plus an orchestral suite Glazunov had just composed. This concert and a rehearsal the previous year gave Rimsky-Korsakov the idea of offering concerts featuring Russian compositions, a prospect to which Belyayev was amenable. The [Symphony Concerts](Russian)(Russian Symphony Concerts) were inaugurated during the 1886–87 season, with Rimsky-Korsakov sharing conducting duties with Anatoly Lyadov.Abraham, *New Grove* (1980), 16:29–30; Zetlin, p. 313. He finished his revision of Mussorgsky's *[on Bald Mountain](Night)(Night on Bald Mountain)* and conducted it at the opening concert.Rimsky-Korsakov, *My Musical Life*, p. 281. The concerts also coaxed him out of his creative drought; he wrote *[Scheherazade](Scheherazade (Rimsky-Korsakov))*, *[Espagnol](Capriccio)(Capriccio Espagnol)* and the *[Easter Overture](Russian)(Russian Easter Overture)* specifically for them. He noted that these three works "show a considerable falling off in the use of contrapuntal devices ... [replaced] by a strong and virtuoso development of every kind of figuration which sustains the technical interest of my compositions".Rimsky-Korsakov, *My Musical Life*, p. 296.

Rimsky-Korsakov was asked for advice and guidance not just on the Russian Symphony Concerts, but on other projects through which Belyayev aided Russian composers. "By force of matters purely musical I turned out to be the head of the Belyayev circle", he wrote. "As the head Belyayev, too, considered me, consulting me about everything and referring everyone to me as chief".Rimsky-Korsakov, *My Musical Life*, p. 288. In 1884 Belyayev set up an annual [prize](Glinka)(Glinka prize), and in 1885 he founded his own music publishing firm, through which he published works by Borodin, Glazunov, Lyadov and Rimsky-Korsakov at his own expense. To select which composers to assist with money, publication or performances from the many who now appealed for help, Belyayev set up an advisory council made up of Glazunov, Lyadov and Rimsky-Korsakov. They would look through the compositions and appeals submitted and suggest which composers were deserving of patronage and public attention.Maes, p. 173.

The group of composers who now congregated with Glazunov, Lyadov and Rimsky-Korsakov became known as the [circle](Belyayev)(Belyayev circle), named after their financial benefactor. These composers were nationalistic in their musical outlook, as The Five before them had been. Like The Five, they believed in a uniquely Russian style of classical music that utilized folk music and exotic melodic, harmonic and rhythmic elements, as exemplified by the music of Balakirev, Borodin and Rimsky-Korsakov. Unlike The Five, these composers also believed in the necessity of an academic, Western-based background in composition—which Rimsky-Korsakov had instilled in his years at the Saint Petersburg Conservatory.Maes, p. 192. Compared to the "revolutionary" composers in Balakirev's circle, Rimsky-Korsakov found those in the Belyayev circle to be "progressive ... attaching as it did great importance to technical perfection, but ... also broke new paths, though more securely, even if less speedily ..."Rimsky-Korsakov, *My Musical Life*, pp. 286–287.

The name of the wealthy patron whose circle Rimsky-Korsakov led, promoting Russian nationalist composers and sponsoring the Russian Symphony Concerts, was **Mitrofan Belyayev** (also spelled M. P. Belaieff). He was a prominent Russian industrialist and music patron who founded the Russian Symphony Concerts and supported composers such as Glazunov, Lyadov, and Rimsky-Korsakov through his publishing firm and advisory council. The group of composers associated with him became known as the **Belyayev circle**.

### Modern fantasy

[[File:Curdie went on after her, flashing his torch about..jpg|thumb|Illustration from 1920 edition of [MacDonald](George)(George MacDonald)'s novel *[Princess and the Goblin](The)(The Princess and the Goblin)*]]

Although pre-dated by [Ruskin](John)(John Ruskin)'s *[King of the Golden River](The)(The King of the Golden River)* (1841), the history of modern fantasy literature is usually said to begin with [MacDonald](George)(George MacDonald), the Scottish author of such novels as *[Princess and the Goblin](The)(The Princess and the Goblin)* and *[Phantastes](Phantastes)* (1858), the latter of which is widely considered to be the first fantasy novel ever written for adults. MacDonald was a major influence on both [R. R. Tolkien](J.)(J. R. R. Tolkien) and [S. Lewis](C.)(C. S. Lewis). The other major fantasy author of this era was [Morris](William)(William Morris), an English poet who wrote several novels in the latter part of the century, including ''[Well at the World's End](The)(The Well at the World's End)''.

Despite MacDonald's future influence with *[the Back of the North Wind](At)(At the Back of the North Wind)* (1871), Morris's popularity with his contemporaries, and [G. Wells](H.)(H. G. Wells)'s *[Wonderful Visit](The)(The Wonderful Visit)* (1895), it was not until the 20th century that fantasy fiction began to reach a large audience. [Dunsany](Lord)(Lord Dunsany) established the genre's popularity in both the novel and the short story form. [Rider Haggard](H.)(H. Rider Haggard), [Kipling](Rudyard)(Rudyard Kipling), and [Rice Burroughs](Edgar)(Edgar Rice Burroughs) began to write fantasy at this time. These authors, along with [Merritt](Abraham)(Abraham Merritt), established what was known as the "lost world" subgenre, which was the most popular form of fantasy in the early decades of the 20th century, although several classic children's fantasies, such as *[Pan](Peter)(Peter Pan)* and *[Wonderful Wizard of Oz](The)(The Wonderful Wizard of Oz)*, were also published around this time.

[fantasy](Juvenile)(Juvenile fantasy) was considered more acceptable than fantasy intended for adults, with the effect that writers who wished to write fantasy had to fit their work into forms aimed at children.[S. Lewis](C.)(C. S. Lewis), "On Juvenile Tastes", p 41, *Of Other Worlds: Essays and Stories*,  [Hawthorne](Nathaniel)(Nathaniel Hawthorne) wrote fantasy in *[Wonder-Book for Girls and Boys](A)(A Wonder-Book for Girls and Boys)*, intended for children,[Attebery](Brian)(Brian Attebery), The Fantasy Tradition in American Literature, p 62,  although works for adults only verged on fantasy. For many years, this and successes such as ''[Adventures in Wonderland](Alice's)(Alice's Adventures in Wonderland)* (1865), created the circular effect that all fantasy works, even the later *[Lord of the Rings](The)(The Lord of the Rings)'', were therefore classified as children's literature.

Political and social trends can affect a society's reception towards fantasy. In the early 20th century, the [Culture Movement](New)(New Culture Movement)'s enthusiasm for Westernization and science in China compelled them to condemn the fantastical [shenmo](shenmo) genre of traditional Chinese literature. The spells and magical creatures of these novels were viewed as superstitious and backward, products of a feudal society hindering the modernization of China. Stories of the supernatural continued to be denounced once the Communists rose to power, and mainland China experienced a revival in fantasy only after the [Revolution](Cultural)(Cultural Revolution) had ended.

Fantasy became a genre of [magazine](pulp)(pulp magazine)s published in the West. In 1923, the first all-fantasy fiction magazine, *[Tales](Weird)(Weird Tales)*, was published. Many other similar magazines eventually followed, including *[Magazine of Fantasy and Science Fiction](The)(The Magazine of Fantasy and Science Fiction)*; when it was founded in 1949, the pulp magazine format was at the height of its popularity, and the magazine was instrumental in bringing fantasy fiction to a wide audience in both the U.S. and Britain. Such magazines were also instrumental in the rise of science fiction, and it was at this time the two genres began to be associated with each other.
